\begin_layout Part
Motion of Extended Body
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fall analysis can be very complex so it is simplified by separating
 the motion into the motion of the center of mass and the rotation about
 the center of mass of the rest of the object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Center of Mass, Reduced Mass and Relative Coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reduced Mass
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 2 mass system.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the external forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{F}_{1}^{ext}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{F}_{2}^{ext}$
\end_inset

 acting on masses 1 and 2.
 If the force on 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 due to 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{F}_{12}$
\end_inset

, then according to Newton's 3rd law, the force om 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 due to 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{F}_{21}=-\underline{F}_{12}\equiv-\underline{F}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations of motion for the two bodies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
m_{1}\underline{\ddot{r}}_{1} & = & \underline{F}_{1}^{ext}+\underline{F}\label{eq:motion of 2 bodies 1}\\
m_{2}\underline{\ddot{r}}_{2} & = & \underline{F}_{2}^{ext}+\underline{F}\label{eq:motion of 2 bodies 2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To makes solving these equations easier, we will simplify the situation.
 Center of mass is given by,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{R}=\frac{m_{1}r_{1}+m_{2}r_{2}}{m_{1}+m_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the relative position is given by,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{r}=\underline{r}_{1}-\underline{r}_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given these definitions, and adding (1) and (2) gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
m_{1}\underline{\ddot{r}}_{1}+m_{2}\underline{\ddot{r}}_{2} & = & \underline{F}_{1}^{ext}+\underline{F}_{2}^{ext}+\underline{F}-\underline{F}\\
(m_{1}+m_{2})\underline{\ddot{R}} & = & \underline{F}_{1}^{ext}+\underline{F}_{2}^{ext}\\
M\underline{\ddot{R}} & = & \underline{F}_{tot}^{ext}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the system behaves like a point mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 at coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under the external force 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{F}_{tot}^{ext}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{F}_{tot}^{ext}=0$
\end_inset

 then the center of mass acceleration is zero and hence the momentum of
 the center of mass is constant.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
M\underline{\ddot{R}} & = & 0\\
\Rightarrow M\underline{\dot{R}} & = & \textrm{constant}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:motion of 2 bodies 1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:motion of 2 bodies 2"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\underline{\ddot{r}}_{1} & = & \frac{\underline{F}_{1}^{ext}}{m_{1}}+\frac{\underline{F}}{m_{1}}\\
\underline{\ddot{r}}_{2} & = & \frac{\underline{F}_{2}^{ext}}{m_{2}}-\frac{\underline{F}}{m_{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Supposing the only external force is gravity, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\underline{F}_{1}^{ext}}{m_{1}}=\frac{\underline{F}_{2}^{ext}}{m_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this is the gravitational acceleration.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Rightarrow\underline{\ddot{r}} & = & \underline{\ddot{r}}_{1}-\underline{\ddot{r}}_{2}=F\left(\frac{1}{m_{1}}+\frac{1}{m_{2}}\right)=\frac{F}{\mu}\\
F & = & \mu\underline{\ddot{r}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{m_{1}m_{2}}{m_{1}+m_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is typically called the reduce mass.
 
\noun on
Reduced mass
\noun default
 
\begin_inset Formula $=\mu$
\end_inset

.
 So the motion of a two body system can be separated into 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
center of mass of the system which moves under the influence of the of the
 net external force and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
relative motion which can be described as the motion of a single particle
 whose mass is the reduced mass, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, under the influence of the internal force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Center of Mass of Many Body System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For two bodies;
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{cm}=\frac{m_{1}r_{1}+m_{2}r_{2}}{m_{1}+m_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For many bodies;
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{cm}=\frac{\sum_{k}^{n}m_{k}\underline{r}_{k}}{\sum_{k}^{n}m_{k}}=\frac{1}{M}\sum_{k}m_{k}\underline{r}_{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the total mass of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a continuous mass distribution;
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{cm}=\frac{\int\underline{r}\mbox{d}m}{\int\mbox{d}m}=\frac{\int\underline{r}\rho(\underline{r})\mbox{d}V}{\int\rho(\underline{r})\mbox{d}V}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\underline{r})=$
\end_inset

 mass density at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finding Center of Mass
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use symmetry where possible
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if the mass distribution has an axis of symmetry, then the center of mass
 will lie on that axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If there is more than one axis of symmetry, then the center of mass must
 lie on both axes, therefor must lie at the point where the axes intersect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is constant, then for a sphere, for example, the center of mass must lie
 at the center of the sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\rho(r)$
\end_inset

 then CM is still at the center,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\rho(z)$
\end_inset

 then CM lies on the z axis.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A solid hemisphere, of uniform density , 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Find the location of the CM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename hemisphere.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By symmetry, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{cm}=y_{cm}=0$
\end_inset

, so just need to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{cm}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the hemisphere as a stack of disks, radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, with height 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{d}m & = & \rho\mbox{d}V\\
 & = & \rho\pi r^{2}\mbox{d}z
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rewrite new variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}=a^{2}-z^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Rightarrow\mbox{d}m & = & \rho\pi(a^{2}-z^{2})\mbox{d}z\\
z_{cm} & = & \frac{\int z\mbox{d}m}{\int\mbox{d}m}\\
 & = & \frac{\int_{0}^{a}\rho\pi z(a^{2}-z^{2})\mbox{d}z}{\int_{0}^{a}\rho\pi(a^{2}-z^{2})\mbox{d}z}\\
 & = & \frac{\int_{0}^{a}za^{2}-z^{3}\mbox{d}z}{\int_{0}^{a}a-z^{2}\mbox{d}z}\\
 & = & \frac{\left[\frac{a^{2}z^{2}}{2}-\frac{z^{4}}{4}\right]_{0}^{a}}{\left[a^{2}z-\frac{z^{3}}{3}\right]_{0}^{a}}=\frac{\frac{a^{4}}{4}}{\frac{2}{3}a^{3}}=\frac{3}{8}a
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a hollow hemisphere,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename hollow hemisphere.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mass per unit area
\begin_inset Formula $=\sigma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Rightarrow\mbox{d}m & = & \sigma\mbox{d}A\\
x_{cm} & = & y_{cm}=0\\
\mbox{d}A & = & 2\pi ra\mbox{d}\theta\\
 & = & 2\pi ra^{2}\sin(\theta)\mbox{d}\theta\\
\mbox{d}m & = & \sigma2\pi a^{2}\sin(\theta)\mbox{d}\theta\\
z & = & a\cos(\theta)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
z_{cm} & = & \frac{\int z\mbox{d}m}{\int\mbox{d}m}\\
 & = & \frac{\int\sigma2\pi a^{2}\sin(\theta)a\cos(\theta)\mbox{d}\theta}{\int\sigma2\pi a^{2}\sin(\theta)\mbox{d}\theta}\\
 & = & \frac{a}{2}\frac{\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}}2\sin(\theta)\cos(\theta)\mbox{d}\theta}{\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\sin(\theta)\mbox{d}\theta}\\
 & = & \frac{a}{2}\frac{\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\sin(2\theta)\mbox{d}\theta}{\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\sin(\theta)\mbox{d}\theta}=\frac{a}{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Harmonic Oscillations and Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Motion in a conservative potential, if the potential depends only on position,
\begin_inset Formula $V=V(r)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E=T+V=\mbox{constant}$
\end_inset

.
 In one dimension this gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\frac{p^{2}}{2m}+V(x)=\mbox{constant}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Types of Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename bounded motion.svg
	scale 200

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a particle with energy E there are three types of region,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a<x<b\qquad$
\end_inset

 - bounded motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $b<x<c\qquad$
\end_inset

 - excluded from the region
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x>c\qquad$
\end_inset

 - unbounded, can travel 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bounded Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a particle in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $a<x<b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x=b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V=E$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mbox{d}V}{\mbox{d}x}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F=-\frac{\mbox{d}V}{\mbox{d}t}<0$
\end_inset

 so the force pushes back towards 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x=a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V=E$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mbox{d}V}{\mbox{d}x}<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F=-\frac{\mbox{d}V}{\mbox{d}t}>0$
\end_inset

 so the force pushes towards 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\therefore$
\end_inset

 Bound particle will oscillate continually between these limits.
 The nature of the oscillation will depend on the shape of the potential
 inside the bounded region.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The point 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, is an equilibrium position for a particle if that particle when released
 from rest at that position doesn't move so remains there, ie the point
 where the net force on an object is zero.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F=-\frac{\mbox{d}V}{\mbox{d}x}=0$
\end_inset

.
 So the equilibrium position is the stationary point in the potential function
 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)$
\end_inset

 have stationary point at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 For small displacement from 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, we expand,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(x)=V_{0}+\left[\frac{\mbox{d}V}{\mbox{d}x}\right]_{x=x_{0}}(x-x_{0})+\left[\frac{\mbox{d}^{2}V}{\mbox{d}x^{2}}\right]_{x=x_{0}}\frac{(x-x_{0})^{2}}{2}+\mathcal{O}(x-x_{0})^{3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, near the equilibrium point,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V(x) & \approx & \left[\frac{\mbox{d}^{2}V}{\mbox{d}x^{2}}\right]_{x=x_{0}}\frac{(x-x_{0})^{2}}{2}+V_{0}\\
\frac{\mbox{d}^{2}V}{\mbox{d}x^{2}} & = & \mbox{constant}=k
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename equilibrium potentail.svg
	scale 200

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\mbox{d}^{2}V}{\mbox{d}x^{2}} & \neq & k\\
F(x) & = & -k(x-x_{0})\\
F & \propto & -\mbox{displacement}\\
 & = & \mbox{resulting force}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So small displacement from the equilibrium will give oscillations about
 the equilibrium,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=m\ddot{x}=-kx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the simple harmonic oscillator.
 So it there is a sufficiently small displacement if any system from the
 equilibrium, that will produce SHM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ddot{x} & = & -\frac{kx}{m}\\
\Rightarrow x(t) & = & Ae^{i\omega t}+Be^{-i\omega t}\\
 & \mbox{or}\\
x(t) & = & C\cos(\omega t)+D\sin(\omega t)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unstable equilibrium
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\mbox{d}^{2}V}{\mbox{d}x^{2}} & < & 0\rightarrow\ddot{x}=\frac{k}{m}x\\
x(t) & = & Ae^{\omega t}+Be^{-\omega t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which corresponds to exponential decrease with time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Simple Pendulum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
