\begin_layout Section
Damping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reality, dissipative forces are usually present.
 These will convert the energy of motion of this oscillator into other forms.
 And so the oscillations will decay.
 The simplest type is one that is proportional to velocity,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=-b\ddot{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the equation of motion becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ddot{x}+b\dot{x}+kx=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mass attached to a light plate that is immersed in a viscous fluid;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
when the mass moves up, the force points downward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
when the mass moves down, the force points upward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
when the mass is at rest there is no net force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ddot{x}+b\dot{x}+kx=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solution, try 
\begin_inset Formula $x=e^{pt}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
(mp^{2}+bp+k)e^{pt} & = & 0\\
mp^{2}+bp+k & = & 0\\
p & = & -\frac{b}{2m}-\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}-\frac{k}{m}}\\
\Rightarrow x(t) & = & Ae^{p_{1}t}+Be^{p_{2}t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{1} & = & -\frac{b}{2m}-\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}-\frac{k}{m}}\\
p_{2} & = & -\frac{b}{2m}+\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}-\frac{k}{m}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ideal SHM 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ddot{y}=ky=0$
\end_inset

.
 With damping 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ddot{y}+b\dot{y}+ky=0$
\end_inset

.
 So the damping force 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\mbox{damp}}=-b\frac{dy}{dt}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
General solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y(t)=Ae^{p_{1}t}+Be^{p_{2}t}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1,2}=-\frac{b}{2m}\pm\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}-\frac{k}{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note, the frequency of the undamped oscillator 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=\sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 So
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{1,2} & = & -\frac{b}{2m}\pm\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}-\frac{k}{m}}=-\frac{b}{2m}\pm\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}-\omega_{0}^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1,2}=\pm i\omega_{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow y(t)=Ae^{i\omega_{0}t}+Be^{-i\omega_{0}t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as expected.
 Get 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 from the initial conditions,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
eg at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=10\unit{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mbox{d}y}{\mbox{d}t}=v=2.6\unit{ms^{-1}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
y(0) & = & A+B=10\\
y`(0) & = & p_{1}A+p_{2}B=2.6
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then solve these simultaneously for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Behavior of Damped Oscillator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two qualitatively different types of behavior, depending on the
 conditions.
 The transition case is a special case that is useful and important for
 many applications.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the case where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}>\frac{k}{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
This means that both 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 are real and negative.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $y=Ae^{p_{1}t}+Be^{p_{2}t}$
\end_inset

, which is that sum of two decaying exponentials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Release an object from rest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Over Damping.svg
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the special case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}=\frac{k}{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow p_{1}=p_{2}=-\frac{b}{2m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the solution has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(t)=(A+B)e^{-\frac{b}{2m}t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Qualitatively this has the same sort of behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Release an object from rest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Critical Damping.svg
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}<\frac{k}{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 are complex
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{1} & = & p_{2}=-\frac{b}{2m}\pm i\omega\\
\Rightarrow y(t) & = & Ae^{p_{1}t}+Be^{p_{2}t}\\
 & = & e^{-\frac{b}{2m}t}\left(Ae^{i\omega t}+Be^{-i\omega t}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can rewrite this as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
y(t) & = & e^{-\frac{b}{2m}t}(C\sin(\omega t)+D\cos(\omega t))\\
 & = & e^{-\frac{b}{2m}t}(C^{2}+D^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}\left(\frac{C}{(C^{2}+D^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}}\cos(\omega t)+\frac{D}{(C^{2}+D^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}}\sin(\omega t)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{C}{(C^{2}+D^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}}=\cos(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{D}{(C^{2}+D^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}}=\sin(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $(C^{2}+D^{2})^{\frac{1}{2}}=E$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
y(t) & = & e^{-\frac{b}{2m}t}E(\cos(\alpha)\cos(\omega t)+\sin(\alpha)\sin(\omega t)\\
 & = & Ee^{-\frac{b}{2m}t}\cos(\omega t-\alpha)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Under Damping.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Frequency of Damped Oscillations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From above
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega^{2}=\frac{k}{m}-\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}=\omega_{0}^{2}-\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So unless the system is very heavily damped 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}\approx\omega_{0}^{2}\textrm{ ie close to critical damping}\right)$
\end_inset

 we usually find that the shift in frequency is not very large, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\approx\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Decay of Damped Oscillations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{-\frac{bt}{2m}}=e^{-\frac{\lambda}{\tau}t}\qquad T=\frac{2\pi}{\omega}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, for each cycle of oscillations, the amplitude decreases by a factor
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\lambda}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{b}{2m} & = & \frac{\lambda}{\frac{2\pi}{\omega}}\\
\lambda & = & \frac{b}{2m}\frac{2\pi}{\omega}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Q Factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=2\pi\frac{\textrm{Energy stored in the oscillator}}{\textrm{Energy dissipated in one cycle}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a dimensionless quantity that relates the loss of energy to the
 cycles made by the oscillator.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textrm{Energy}\propto\textrm{(Amplitude)}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Q value.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the fraction of energy lost per cycle (change in energy)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\Delta E}{E} & = & \frac{A_{3}}{A_{1}}\frac{A_{1}^{2}-A_{3}^{2}}{A_{1}^{2}}\qquad\frac{A_{3}}{A_{1}}=e^{-\lambda}\\
\frac{\Delta E}{E} & = & 1-\frac{A_{3}^{2}}{A_{1}^{2}}=1-e^{-2\lambda}\\
\therefore Q & = & 2\pi\frac{\Delta E}{E}=\frac{2\pi}{1-e^{-2\lambda}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When damping is very light, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\ll1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1-e^{-2\lambda} & \approx & 2\lambda\\
\Rightarrow Q & \approx & \frac{\pi}{\lambda}=\frac{m\omega}{b}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Large Q
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Light damping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Little energy lost per cycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename large Q.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Small Q
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Heavy damping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lots of energy lost per cycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename small Q.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Forced Damped Simple Harmonic Oscillations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the system with
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Restoring force 
\begin_inset Formula $=ky$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Damping force 
\begin_inset Formula $=b\dot{y}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Periodic driving force 
\begin_inset Formula $=F_{0}\cos(\omega t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Equation of motion
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
m\ddot{y} & = & -ky-b\dot{y}+F_{0}\cos(\omega t)\\
m\ddot{y}+ky+b\dot{y} & = & F_{0}\cos(\omega t)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a second order, non homogeneous differential equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
General Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textrm{General Solution}=\textrm{Particular Integral}+\textrm{Complimentary Function}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Why study this example?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many examples of other forced systems, but many of these are not
 sinusoidal in their forces.
 Study the sinusoidal forced oscillations because,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
its the easiest to study
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it does have many important applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
any other force can be rewritten as a set of interfering sinusoidal waves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This uses the fact that this equation is linear.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are solutions of the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
m\ddot{y}_{1}+ky_{1}+b\dot{y}_{1} & = & A\cos(\omega_{1}t)\\
m\ddot{y}_{2}+ky_{2}+b\dot{y}_{2} & = & A\sin(\omega_{2}t)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then 
\begin_inset Formula $y=y_{1}+y_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the solution of the following equation which is the same operator being
 driven by the sum of those two forces,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ddot{y}+ky+b\dot{y}=A\cos(\omega_{1}t)+B\sin(\omega_{2}t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Solving the Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\omega t)$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\omega t}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Rightarrow m\ddot{y}+b\dot{y}+ky=F_{0}e^{i\omega t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solve these two equations together then take the real part of y as the solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Particular integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Try 
\begin_inset Formula $y=Ae^{i\omega t}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A(-m\omega^{2}+ib\omega+k)e^{i\omega t} & = & F_{0}e^{i\omega t}\\
A & = & \frac{F_{0}}{m}\frac{1}{-\omega^{2}+\frac{k}{m}+\frac{i\omega b}{m}}\\
A & = & \frac{F_{0}}{m}\frac{1}{(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})+i\omega\frac{b}{m}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rewrite in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $A=A_{0}e^{i\phi}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{0}=\sqrt{c^{2}+a^{2}},\qquad\tan\phi=\frac{b}{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Giving
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{0}=\frac{F_{0}}{m}\frac{1}{\left((\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})+\frac{\omega^{2}b^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{-\omega b}{m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convention dictates this is written as phase angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=-\phi$
\end_inset

, giving
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(t)=A_{0}e^{i(\omega t+\phi)}=A_{0}e^{i(\omega t-\alpha)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the real part of the solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(t)=A_{0}\cos(\omega t-\alpha)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $-\alpha$
\end_inset

is the phase difference between the applied force and the response of the
 oscillator to it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Complimentary function 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ddot{y}+b\dot{y}+ky=0$
\end_inset

, from unforced example.
 Since the complimentary function decays with time, it describes a transient
 response to initial conditions.
 For large times, 
\begin_inset Formula $CF\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and only 
\begin_inset Formula $PI$
\end_inset

 is left.
 Therefore we will ignore 
\begin_inset Formula $CF$
\end_inset

 and consider the steady state behavior described by 
\begin_inset Formula $PI$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constant Force 
\begin_inset Formula $(b=0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{0}=\frac{F_{0}}{m\omega_{0}^{2}}=\frac{F_{0}}{k}\qquad(\textrm{Hoches Law})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Without Damping 
\begin_inset Formula $(b=0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A_{0} & = & \frac{F_{0}}{m(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})}\rightarrow\infty\qquad\textrm{when }\omega=\omega_{0}\\
\alpha & = & \tan^{-1}(0)=0,\pm\pi
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega & < & \omega_{0},\; A>0,\;\alpha=0\qquad\textrm{oscillates in phase with the force}\\
\omega & > & \omega_{0},\; A<0,\;\alpha=\pi\qquad\textrm{oscillates in antiphase}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename oscillating without damping.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Forced Oscillations with Damping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resonant frequency
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{0}=\frac{F}{m}\left(\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{\omega^{2}b^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)^{-\frac{1}{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximum when there is a turning point,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\partial A}{\partial\omega} & = & 0\\
\Rightarrow\omega_{\mbox{res}}^{2} & = & \omega_{0}^{2}-\frac{b^{2}}{2m^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the resonant frequency of the damped oscillator is
\begin_inset Formula $<\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Though is the damping is light, the difference is very small.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\textrm{Resonant Frequency} & \neq & \textrm{Natural Frequency of damped oscillator}\\
\omega_{\mbox{res}}^{2} & = & \omega_{0}^{2}-\frac{b^{2}}{2m^{2}}\\
\omega_{\mbox{damp}}^{2} & = & \omega_{0}^{2}-\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resonant frequency is the lowest.
 The damping force is proportional to the velocity, so increasing the velocity
 means that the damping force increases too, so the higher frequencies provide
 more force.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Amplitude of Resonance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\mbox{res}}=\frac{F_{0}}{m}\left(\frac{1}{\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega_{\mbox{res}}^{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{\omega_{\mbox{\mbox{re}s}}^{2}b^{2}}{m^{2}}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{res}$
\end_inset

 from above,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A_{\mbox{res}} & = & \frac{F_{0}}{m}\left(\frac{1}{\frac{b^{2}}{m^{2}}\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}\right)}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\\
A_{\mbox{res}} & = & \frac{F_{0}}{b\omega_{\mbox{damp}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As expected, the heavier damping leads to smaller amplitude at resonance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Amplitude and Q Factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When there is light damping,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Q & \apprge & \frac{m\omega_{\mbox{damp}}}{b}\\
b & = & \frac{m\omega_{\mbox{damp}}}{Q}\\
\Rightarrow A_{\mbox{res}} & = & \frac{F_{0}Q}{m\omega_{\mbox{damp}}^{2}}\\
A_{\mbox{res}} & \propto & Q
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, for light damping,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega_{\mbox{damp}}^{2} & \approx & \omega_{0}^{2}=\frac{k}{m}\\
\Rightarrow A_{\mbox{res}} & = & \frac{F_{0}}{k}Q
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, the amplitude at resonance is the Quality factor times the constant
 displacement caused by a force of the same magnitude with no oscillations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Width of Resonance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the width as the full width at half maximum of 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename full width half maximum.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{2}=\frac{F_{0}^{2}}{m^{2}}\frac{1}{\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{b^{2}\omega^{2}}{m^{2}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 for which the denominator is doubled, ie has twice the resonant value,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{b^{2}\omega^{2}}{m^{2}}=2\times\left(\frac{b^{2}\omega_{0}^{2}}{m^{2}}-\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider light damping, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{b^{2}}{4m^{2}}\ll\omega_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{b^{2}\omega^{2}}{m^{2}} & \approx & \frac{2b^{2}\omega_{0}^{2}}{m^{2}}\\
\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)^{2} & = & \frac{b^{2}\omega^{2}}{m^{2}}+\frac{b^{2}}{m^{2}}\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Near resonance 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\ll\omega_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)^{2} & \approx & \frac{b^{2}\omega_{0}^{2}}{m^{2}}\\
\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} & = & \pm\frac{b\omega_{0}}{m}\\
\left(\omega_{0}-\omega\right)\left(\omega_{0}+\omega\right) & = & \pm\frac{b\omega_{0}}{m}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\approx\omega\rightarrow\omega_{0}+\omega=2\omega_{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
2\omega_{0}\left(\omega_{0}-\omega\right) & \approx & \pm\frac{b\omega_{0}}{m}\\
\frac{\omega_{0}-\omega}{\omega_{0}} & = & \pm\frac{b}{2m\omega}=\pm\frac{1}{2Q}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives the half width, so the full width at half maximum (FWHM) frequency
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 So light damping, ie a large Q value, gives a narrow amplitude with a large
 resonance.
 As the damping gets heavier, the width and the amplitude decrease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename light and heavy damping.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Phase of Oscillator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{b\omega}{m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\tan\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\rightarrow\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 so, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(\omega_{0}\right)\rightarrow\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So the phase of the oscillator does not depend of the damping.
 We still have the phase switch, but it is softened by the damping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename light and heavy damping phase.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Rotational Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Angular Momentum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The angular momentum of an object, relative to the origin of co-ordinates
 is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{L}=\underline{r}\times\underline{p}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{r}$
\end_inset

 is the position vector from the origin and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{p}$
\end_inset

 is the momentum vector.
 This has the dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $[M][L^{2}][T^{-1}]$
\end_inset

, but has no named standard unit.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{p}$
\end_inset

, therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

 will be normal to the plane of rotation of the object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plane of rotation.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The direction is given by the right hand rule, there is no position in space
 linked with the angular momentum, just a magnitude and direction.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

 depends on where 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{p}$
\end_inset

 are measured from.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Block standing along the axis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename block sliding on the axis.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relative to the origin, 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\underline{L} & = & \underline{r}_{1}\times\underline{p}\\
 & = & \underline{y}\times m\underline{v}=\underline{0}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relative to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\underline{L} & = & \underline{r}_{1}\times\underline{p}\\
 & = & \begin{pmatrix}0\\
y\\
-a
\end{pmatrix}\times\begin{pmatrix}0\\
mv\\
0
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & = & mva\hat{\underline{x}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{v}$
\end_inset

 is constant, then so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

 depends on the distance of closest approach, but not on the instantaneous
 position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conical Pendulum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename conical pendulum.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are the same situation so the angular momentum should be able to be
 used to describe the motion, irrespective of the chosen co-ordinate system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Forces and Rotation: Torque
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of forces on rotation is described by its torque,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\underline{r}\times\underline{F}=\underline{r}\times\frac{\mbox{d}p}{\mbox{d}t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So torques are perpendicular to the forces producing it.
 Like the angular momentum, the magnitude of the torque depends on where
 it is measured from, the co-ordinate system used.
 So you can have a torque with no net force, and a force with no net torque.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename torque vs force.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the change in angular momentum,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\mbox{d}\underline{L}}{\mbox{d}t} & = & \frac{\mbox{d}}{\mbox{d}t}(\underline{r}\times\underline{p})\\
 & = & \frac{\mbox{d}\underline{r}}{\mbox{d}t}\times\underline{p}+\underline{r}\times\frac{\mbox{d}\underline{p}}{\mbox{d}t}\\
 & = & \underline{v}\times m\underline{v}+\underline{r}\times\frac{\mbox{d}\underline{p}}{\mbox{d}t}\\
 & = & \underline{r}\times\underline{F}=\tau\\
\Rightarrow\tau & = & \frac{\mbox{d}\underline{L}}{\mbox{d}t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the torque is the change in angular momentum per unit time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
\noun on
Ex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conical pendulum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename conical pendulum forces.svg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tension must balance the weight,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T\cos(\alpha)-mg & = & 0\\
T & = & \frac{mg}{\cos(\alpha)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\therefore$
\end_inset

the net force
\begin_inset Formula $=$
\end_inset

horizontal component of the tension,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{F_{r}}=-T\sin(\alpha)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Measure everything relative to the center of rotation, 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\underline{\tau} & = & \underline{r}\times\underline{F}=\underline{\tau}\times\underline{F_{r}}=0\\
\frac{\mbox{d}\underline{L}}{\mbox{d}t} & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
therefore, in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

 is constant
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\underline{L} & = & \underline{r}\underline{p}\\
 & = & \underline{l}\sin(\alpha)p\underline{\hat{z}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Measure relative to the pivot, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\underline{L}|=|\underline{l}\times\underline{p}|=lp=lmr\omega=\textrm{constant}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{L}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
